I am using the Java Media Framework 2.1.1e (including Windows booster pack) for 
a small application I wrote in Eclipse 2.1 on Windows XP (same happens on 
Windows 2000).

The program seeks for a specified cam, shows the live video in a dialog and when 
the dialog is closed captures on image.

The program runs fine with the "default classpath", consisting of the JRE plus 
the project, plus jmf.lib from the Java Media Framework 2.1.1.e.

The program crashes with this message when I am using exactly the same classpath 
but removing the "[X] default classpath" checkmark in the run environment!

This is scary because there is actually no difference in the classpath, so it 
seems to be a bug.

When I am using the "export" function of Eclipse to create a jar, and run that 
jar from outside of Eclipse, the bug is gone and my program shows a running live 
video! So it seems to be really a bug of the "run environment" inside of 
Eclipse!

Here is the exception I am getting:

java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: JMFSecurityManager: java.lang.
UnsatisfiedLinkError: no jmvfw in java.library.path
	at com.sun.media.JMFSecurityManager.loadLibrary(JMFSecurityManager.java:
206)
